05159nam a22008535i 9783110720792DE-B159720230228015514.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20212021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107207927 a10.1515/97831107207922doi  a(DE-B1597)567929  a(OCoLC)1266228044  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aREL1140002bisacsh1 aTapani Tekoniemi, Timo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Textual History of 2 Kings 17 /cTimo Tapani Tekoniemi. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (XII, 311 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBeihefte zur Zeitschrift für die alttestamentliche Wissenschaft ,x0934-2575 ;v53600tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgements -- tContents -- t1 Introduction -- t2 The textual history of verses 1–23 in light of documented evidence -- t3 Literary and redactional analysis of verses 7–23 -- t4 The textual history of verses 24–41 -- t5 Conclusions: the textual history of 2Kgs 17 -- tAppendices -- tAbbreviations -- tBibliographical abbreviations -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Ancient Sources -- tIndex of Modern Authors -- tSubject index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe textual history of the Books of Kings forms one of the most complex and debated issues in the modern text-historical scholarship. This book examines and reconstructs the textual history of 2 Kings 17 in light of the preserved textual evidence. The analysis of textual differences between the LXX, the Old Latin, and the MT allows the reconstruction of the oldest text attainable. The Old Latin version appears to have in many cases best preserved the Old Greek edition of the chapter, now lost in the Greek witnesses due to Hebraizing revisions. The Old Greek version of 2 Kings 17 evidences a Hebrew Vorlage often radically differing from the MT. In most cases the MT exhibits signs of later editing. The LXX can thus help the scholars reconstruct multiple text-historical layers previously out of our reach, as well as shed new light on certain historiographical details recounted in 2 Kings 17. As supposed by the literary critics for well over a century, the textual data shows beyond doubt that there happened vast editing and rewriting of the Books of Kings even at very late date. Text-critical considerations are therefore not only useful, but invaluable to all scholarly work on 2 Kings 17, and the Books of Kings as a whole.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4a2 Könige. 4aRedaktionskritik. 4aSeptuaginta. 4aTextkritik. 7aRELIGION / Ancient.2bisacsh  a2 Kings.  aSeptuagint.  aredaction criticism.  atextual criticism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2021z978311075072008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2021 Part 1z978311075070608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2021 Englishz978311075419308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2021z9783110753974oZDB-23-DGF0 cEPUBz97831107208530 cprintz978311072076140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311072079240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110720792423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110720792/original  a978-3-11-075070-6  DG Plus DeG Package 2021 Part 1b2021  a978-3-11-075072-0  DG Ebook Package English 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-1